[Scarlet fever is caused by erythrogenic toxin-producing group A streptococci (GAS) (_Streptococcus pyogenes_), and usually follows streptococcal pharyngitis, but may also follow streptococcal infection of the skin or soft tissue, such as wounds, burns, or the uterus (that is, puerperal scarlet fever). Scarlet fever usually occurs in children. By the age of 10 years, most people will have developed immunity.

Scarlet fever is highly contagious. Transmission occurs via airborne respiratory particles dispersed from infected patients by coughing or sneezing, usually in the colder winter months, or through contact with infected wounds or sores on the skin. Those who carry the bacteria in the nasopharynx or on the skin but have no symptoms are less contagious (http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dbmd/diseaseinfo/groupastreptococcal_g.htm).

Over a century ago, scarlet fever was feared as a potentially lethal disease. Its mortality and morbidity waned, however, well before antibiotics became available. Since the advent of antibiotic therapy, the mortality rate of treated scarlet fever has been less than one percent. Community-wide outbreaks still occur, as happened in Hong Kong in 2011; (see prior ProMED-mail posts in 2011 on scarlet fever in Hong Kong).

For a more detailed discussion of scarlet fever, please see the prior ProMED-mail posts Streptococcus, group A, scarlet fever - Guernsey 20110217.0521 and Streptococcus, group A, scarlet fever, fatal - China: (HK) RFI 20110622.1906.

Lincolnshire is a historic county in the east of England. It lies along the North Sea coast with Cambridgeshire to the south, Rutland to the southwest, Leicestershire and Nottinghamshire to the west, South Yorkshire to the northwest, and the East Riding of Yorkshire to the north. The county town is Lincoln. For a map of England's counties, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Administrative_counties_of_England. The county town is Lincoln. - Mod.ML

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/9BtQ.]
